1 of injury unless the insurer, self-insured employer or assigned claims agent for a noncomplying em-
2 ployer receives:
3 (A) Within 30 days of receipt of the initial claim, notice that the worker was employed in more
4 than one job with a subject employer at the time of injury; and
5 (B) Within 60 days of the date of mailing a request for verification, verifiable documentation of
6 wages from such additional employment.
7 (c) Notwithstanding ORS 656.005 (7)(c), an injury to a worker employed in more than one job
8 at the time of injury is not disabling if no temporary disability benefits are payable for time lost
9 from the job at injury. Claim costs incurred as a result of supplemental temporary disability benefits
10 paid as provided in subsection (5) of this section may not be included in any data used for
11 ratemaking or individual employer rating or dividend calculations by an insurer, a rating organiza-
12 tion licensed pursuant to ORS chapter 737, the State Accident Insurance Fund Corporation or the
13 Department of Consumer and Business Services if the injured worker is not eligible for permanent
14 disability benefits or temporary disability benefits for time lost from the job at injury.
15 (d) For the purpose of this section:
16 (A) The benefits of a worker who incurs an injury shall be based on the wage of the worker at
17 the time of injury.
18 (B) The benefits of a worker who incurs an occupational disease shall be based on the wage of
19 the worker at the time there is medical verification that the worker is unable to work because of
20 the disability caused by the occupational disease. If the worker is not working at the time that there
21 is medical verification that the worker is unable to work because of the disability caused by the
22 occupational disease, the benefits shall be based on the wage of the worker at the worker’s last
23 regular employment.
24 (e) As used in this subsection, “regularly employed” means actual employment or availability for
25 such employment. For workers not regularly employed and for workers with no remuneration or
26 whose remuneration is not based solely upon daily or weekly wages, the Director of the Department
27 of Consumer and Business Services, by rule, may prescribe methods for establishing the worker’s
28 weekly wage.
29 (3) No disability payment is recoverable for temporary total or partial disability suffered during
30 the first three calendar days after the worker leaves work or loses wages as a result of the
31 compensable injury unless the worker is totally disabled after the injury and the total disability
32 continues for a period of 14 consecutive days or unless the worker is admitted as an inpatient to a
33 hospital within 14 days of the first onset of total disability. If the worker leaves work or loses wages
34 on the day of the injury due to the injury, that day shall be considered the first day of the three-day
35 period.
36 (4) When an injured worker with an accepted disabling compensable injury is required to leave
37 work to receive compensable medical services for the compensable injury, the worker shall receive
38 temporary disability benefits calculated pursuant to ORS 656.212 for the period during which the
39 worker is absent, until such time as the worker is determined to be medically stationary. However,
40 benefits under this subsection are not payable if wages are paid for the period of absence by the
41 employer. An insurer may require a worker to confirm the period during which the worker is absent
42 from work to receive compensable medical services under this subsection. The notice requirement
43 under ORS 656.262 (4)(j) does not apply to temporary disability benefits paid pursuant to this sub-
44 section.
45 (5)(a) The insurer of the employer at injury or the self-insured employer at injury, may elect to
